    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-09-08_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <dateline>
                    <date when="1818-09-08"></date></dateline>
                
                
                    <note>30</note><lb/>
                    <p>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bowood-House_ENK">Bowood</placeName> Tuesday Sep<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                    8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. - we arrived here <choice> 
                    <orig>yes-<lb/>
                    terday</orig>
                    <reg>yesterday</reg>
                    </choice>
                    to dinner &amp; were<lb/>
                    most cordially received<lb/>
                    - no one here but M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Dumont<lb/>
                    - a young French <hi rend="underline">judge</hi> -<lb/>
                    and Sir George Paul - gone<lb/>
                    both this morning - no<lb/>
                    company expected for<lb/>
                    some days -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    Your letter to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> of<lb/>
                    the 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Sep reached us just<lb/>
                    as we were getting into<lb/>
                    the carriage to come here<lb/>
                    - But yours &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovells</persName> which<lb/>
                    you mention as having<lb/>
                    sent by M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Lees's frank<lb/>
                    has not yet reached us<lb/>
                    - and most anxious we<lb/>
                    are to receive it - The <choice> 
                    <orig>mo<lb/>
                     ment</orig>
                    <reg>moment</reg>
                    </choice>
                    I receive it I will<lb/>
                    write<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-09-08_page02.jpg"/>
                    I now merely write this<lb/>
                    time in utmost haste to<lb/>
                    say we are at last where<lb/>
                    you, kindest of friends,<lb/>
                    have so much wished us<lb/>
                    to be - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> is well &amp;<lb/>
                    tho thin looked extremely<lb/>
                    pretty &amp; nice yesterday at<lb/>
                    dinner - Miss Wilkinson<lb/>
                    &amp; Miss Briscoe have done<lb/>
                    all you could have wished<lb/>
                    for her - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady Lansdowne</persName><lb/>
                    is very kind in her <choice> 
                    <orig>man-<lb/>
                    ner</orig>
                    <reg>manner</reg>
                    </choice>
                    towards her - I think<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady L</persName> just the same <choice> 
                    <orig>per<lb/>
                     -son</orig>
                     <reg>person</reg>
                    </choice>
                    - only fatter &amp; more<lb/>
                    formed in manner.<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    This place as far as I can<lb/>
                    judge not naturally <choice> 
                    <orig>hand<lb/>
                    some</orig>
                    <reg>handsome</reg>
                    </choice>
                    - the house <choice> 
                    <orig>magnifi<lb/>
                    cent</orig>
                    <reg>magnificent</reg>
                    </choice>
                    - Our rooms opening<lb/>
                    one into another just what<lb/>
                
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-09-08_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>31</note><lb/>
                    you would wish for us -<lb/>
                    George lodged near us -<lb/>
                    He is well &amp; I believe happy<lb/>
                    - and desires poor Molly<lb/>
                    sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be told he is well.<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    I send this note through<lb/>
                    M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ward - and send many<lb/>
                    letters as the shortest <choice> 
                    <orig>me-<lb/>
                    thod</orig>
                    <reg>method</reg>
                    </choice>
                    of communicating<lb/>
                    many things to you which<lb/>
                    I literally have not time<lb/>
                    to copy -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    I have just written to my<lb/>
                    Aunt R. the first letter<lb/>
                    since one from Bangor,<lb/>
                    - I have copied <hi rend="underline">rs</hi> her from<lb/>
                    Dumonts letter all that<lb/>
                    relates to the M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>. -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    I long to rest my mind by<lb/>
                    going to my <hi rend="underline">work</hi> again -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    What a contrast between<lb/>
                    all <del>the <unclear></unclear></del> round us<lb/>
                    at this moment and all at<lb/>
                
                <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-09-08_page04.jpg"/>
                    home -!<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    I <hi rend="underline">endeavor</hi> dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> to hope<lb/>
                    that this sleep so sound &amp;<lb/>
                    often repeated will restore<lb/>
                    him - But a secret feeling<lb/>
                    at the bottom of my mind<lb/>
                    arising I believe from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramP1"><choice> 
                    <orig>Cramp<lb/>
                    ton</orig>
                    <reg>Crampton</reg>
                    </choice></persName>
                    predictions &amp; <hi rend="underline">his</hi> likeness<lb/>
                    to Henry make me tremble -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    I agree with you that if<lb/>
                    he does not recover it will<lb/>
                    be better to place him in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK"><choice> 
                    <orig>Eng-<lb/>
                    land</orig>
                    <reg>England</reg>
                    </choice></placeName>
                    than any where in<lb/>
                    land than anywhere in<lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> - the worst place in<lb/>
                    the world for the reasons<lb/>
                    you mention would be<lb/>
                    M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Fox's -<lb/></p>
                
                <closer>
                    I am called away<lb/>
                    affec<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName><lb/>
                </closer>
                
                
               <postscript> <p> 
                       I find that <del>mem</del> Lord &amp; Lady<lb/>
                       Grenville are to be here<lb/>
                       tomorrow.<lb/>
                       I must answer that I cannot<lb/>
                       recommend a governess -<lb/>
                       for I dont know of a good<lb/>
                       one - <hi rend="underline">do you?</hi> - <hi rend="underline">answer</hi> this<lb/>
                       Maria Sept<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                       1818<lb/>
               </p> </postscript>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
            </div>
